					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Otherwise it seems like the proportions are off. I mean, when drawing the head should take at least 1/7 of total body height, but in a video game context it's often way more, up to 1/2 for cartoon proportions.</div><br />It really depends on the art style you want to put forth. The <a href="https://allthetropes.orain.org/wiki/Graphics_Induced_Super_Deformed" class="postlink">graphics-induced super-deformed</a> art style inflates the head to make a face recognizable; a more proportional art style relies on things other than the face. Compare, for example, <em>Super Mario Bros. 3</em> to <em>Contra</em>.<div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<span class="gensmall"><b>File comment:</b> Length of red line in front of each character's face is the height of the head, assuming removal of hat, and excluding outlines.<br />Mario: 11 pixels<br />Bill Rizer: 5 pixels</span><br />
		
			<img src="./download/file.php?id=1627" alt="head_size_options.png" /><br />
			<span class="gensmall">head_size_options.png [ 475 Bytes | Viewed 1023 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Even if you don't want a cartoon look, you should at least make head 1/5 of body height. I haven't checked but here it looks more like 1/10.</div><br />I just checked in GIMP, and this graphic is 1/6.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Also either go for cartoon proportions and caroon hair, or realistic proportions and realistic hair. Realistic proportions and cartoon hair is a bit weird.</div><br />Yet realistic head size combined with <a href="https://allthetropes.orain.org/wiki/You_Gotta_Have_Blue_Hair" class="postlink">fantastic hair</a> is the standard in manga and anime.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Finally is this for the NES ? It doesn't looks like it use few enough colours.</div><br />The 32x64 pixel frame is also wider than one might expect for NES, where characters rarely exceed 24 pixels wide. I'm under the impression that PPT is more of a Super NES pixel artist.</div>

